}}
Upon release, the game was positively reviewed. It drew favorable comparisons to both ''[[Berzerk (video game)|Berzerk]]'' and ''[[Gauntlet (1985 video game)|Gauntlet]]'' for its maze-like stages and shooting gameplay.<ref name="TGM" /><ref name="Crash">{{cite news|title=Xybots|publisher=Crash|date=May 1988|pages=34–35|url=https://www.solvalou.com/subpage/arcade_reviews/77/407/xybots_review.html}}</ref> The game's various features, including the cooperative gameplay, were praised, with ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' and ''[[The Games Machine]]'' citing them as aspects that made the game addictive.<ref name="CVG" /><ref name="TGM" /> ''[[Commodore User]]'' also cited the two-player game as a highlight, saying "its real appeal is as a team game, with you and your mate running about the place, covering each other, dividing up and destroying all the robots in the maze, and lending one another gold coins in the shop."<ref name="CU" />

Ed Logg recalled in 2005 that the game was not a financial success. ''[[GamesTM]]'' wrote that "''Xybots'' was overlooked in arcades due to its complex controls and tricky gameplay" and that its lack of earnings in arcades was the reason no sequel was ever developed. In retrospect, they wrote that the game was "ahead of its time" and "offered a unique experience that similar games of the era were unable to match."<ref name="GTM" />

==Ports==
[[Image:Xybots.jpg|thumb|Lynx box art by Marc Ericksen]]

In 1989 ''Xybots'' was [[ported]] to [[MSX]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Amstrad]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Atari ST]], and [[Amiga]]. In 1991, the Atari Games subsidiary [[Tengen (company)|Tengen]] released a version of the game for the handheld [[Atari Lynx]], developed by the Chicago-based [[NuFX]].<ref name="GTM" />

A version for the [[Sega Genesis]] by  Tengen had been announced at the 1990 Winter [[Consumer Electronics Show]] alongside ports of the Atari Games titles ''[[Paperboy (video game)|Paperboy]]'' and ''[[Hard Drivin']]'',<ref name="EGM">{{cite magazine|title=Outpost: Genesis|last=Harris|first=Steve|date=April 1990|publisher=Sendai|magazine=Electronic Gaming Monthly|page=73}}</ref> but while the latter two games were released for the system, ''Xybots'' was not. A planned [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] port from Tengen also went unreleased.<ref>{{cite web |title=Xybots [NES – Unreleased] |url=https://www.unseen64.net/2008/04/11/xybots-nes-unreleased/ |website=Unseen64 |date=11 April 2008 |access-date=28 August 2022}}</ref>

==Legacy==
Having acquired the rights to the Atari Games arcade library through its parent company [[WMS Industries|Williams]],<ref name="NG">{{cite magazine|title=Time Warner to Quit Game Business|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]]|issue=21 |publisher=[[Imagine Media]]|date=September 1996|page=15}}</ref> Midway released the arcade version of Xybots as part of the 2004 console compilation ''[[Midway Arcade Treasures 2]]'',<ref name="GameSpot">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/action/midwayarcadetreasuresii/review.html |title=Midway Arcade Treasures 2 Review |publisher=GameSpot.com |date=2004-10-11 |access-date=2013-01-09}}</ref> as well as ''[[Midway Arcade Treasures Deluxe Edition]]'' for [[Microsoft Windows]].<ref name="GZ">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamezone.com/reviews/midway_arcade_treasures_deluxe_edition_pc_review/|title=Midway Arcade Treasures: Deluxe Edition - PC - Review|date=May 4, 2012|access-date=March 15, 2018|publisher=GameZone}}</ref> The arcade version also saw release on the [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]] as part of ''[[Midway Arcade Treasures Extended Play]]''.<ref name="GameSpotPSP">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/midway-arcade-treasures-extended-play-review/1900-6141337/ |title=Midway Arcade Treasures Extended Play Review |publisher=GameSpot.com |date=2005-12-01 |access-date=2018-03-15}}</ref>

With the dissolution of Midway in 2009, [[Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment]] picked up the rights to Midway's arcade titles,<ref name=WarnerOKd>{{cite news|last=Dunca|first=Geoff|url=http://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/time-warner-buying-most-of-midway-games-for-33-mln/|title=Time Warner Buying Most of Midway Games for $33 Mln|access-date=2009-07-06|work=Digital Trends|archive-date=2010-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101230034624/http://www.digitaltrends.com/gaming/time-warner-buying-most-of-midway-games-for-33-mln/|url-status=dead}}</ref> releasing ''Xybots'' for the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[Xbox 360]] as part of ''[[Midway Arcade Origins]]''<ref name="IGN">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/11/14/midway-arcade-origins-review|title=Midway Arcade Origins review|publisher=IGN|date=November 14, 2012|access-date=March 15, 2018}}</ref> and for various other platforms through the ''[[Lego Dimensions]]'' Midway Arcade Level Pack.<ref name="Polygon">{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/3/24/11296570/lego-dimensions-midway-arcade-interview|title=Lego Dimensions Delivers a Playable Video Game Museum with Midway Arcade|date=March 24, 2016|access-date=March 15, 2018|publisher=Vox Media|work=Polygon|last=Crecente|first=Brian}}</ref>

